<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-11-18T22:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-11-18T22:00:00-05:00" n="554" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d554">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/13734: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-11-19T11:00:00+08:00">November 19, 1936—11
                                    a.m.</date><lb/>[Received November 19—6:50 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>558. Embassy’s 540, November 12, 4 p.m. Tientsin communicated notice to
                            Americans resident in Suiyuan and Ningsia and advised them if they found
                            themselves endangered, or if the situation gave promise of developing in
                            such a way as to threaten their position, they should withdraw to a
                            place of safety. Several Americans have already withdrawn from Suiyuan.
                            No report from Hankow.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
